    "## Task 5: Countries with longevity (4 points)\n",
    "\n",
    "In this task we return to the life expectancy dataset used in homeworks 01 and 02. The code below imports the table and shows the first 5 lines.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "url = \"https://fmfi-compbio.github.io/viz/data/life_expectancy_years.csv\"\n",
    "life_exp = pd.read_csv(url)\n",
    "life_exp.set_index('Country', inplace=True)\n",
    "display(life_exp.head())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here we will consider only the portion of table `life_exp` corresponding to years from 1980 to 1999 (inclusive). You can start by selecting only columns for these years and storing them in a new table called `table20`. Note that you can use slices in `loc` and unlike slices in `iloc` and Python lists, these slices are [inclusive](https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/advanced.html#endpoints-are-inclusive), meaning that `'1980':'1981'` are two columns of the table whereas in normal slices 0:1 means just column 0. \n",
    "\n",
    "Our goal is to select countries which have in each of these years (1980 to 1999) higher or equal life expectancy than France. We can achieve this easily with [boolean indexing](https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/indexing.html#boolean-indexing). In homework 02, we compare two `Series` using `<`. Here we will do a similar thing with rows of the table, but we will use function [`ge`](https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.ge.html) instead of `<=`. We will compare the whole `table20` to a single row for France (which you need to select first) using `ge` with optional parameter `axis=1`. This will compare each row of the table with the row for France and the result will be a `DataFrame` filled with booleans saying if in a particular year a particular country has worse or better life expectancy than France.\n",
    "\n",
    "To finish our anaysis, we need to compute logical *and* of all values in one row of the boolean table to obtain a single column and to use this column to select rows from `table20`. The logical *and* of all values in a row is computed using [`all(axis=1)`](https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.all.html). Store the result in `DataFrame` `task5`; it should contain five countries (including France itself) and for each all life expectancy values for years 1980 to 1999."
   ]
